\section{Replication of LinUCB}

In the current section we aim to demonstrate how \pkg{contextual} facilitates the comparison of bandit policies on big offline data sets by replicating the main results of \cite{Li2010}'s seminal "A Contextual-Bandit Approach to Personalized News Article Recommendation". The paper describes how the authors ran an offline Li bandit such as the one outlined in the previous section to evaluate the effectiveness of several contextual and non-contextual policies by training and comparing them on click through data drawn from the Today news module on the Yahoo! homepage over the course of several days in May 2009. With a data set of 45,811,883 separate, random and unbiased events (made available at the Yahoo! lab's website\footnote{At https://webscope.sandbox.yahoo.com/catalog.php?datatype=r\&did=49}) it is a perfect candidate for showcasing \pkg{contextual}'s ability to evaluate multiple policies in parallel.

For the details on the data structure and the general setup of the experiment, I refer the reader to \cite{Chu2009} and to the original \cite{Li2010} paper. In brief, each row in the Yahoo! data set describes an interaction event (click or no click) of users shown a randomly chosen article. Each of these events contains information on (I) a random article chosen to be positioned at the story position on top of the Today module on Yahoo!'s website (II) six features per article for each of the articles shown below the article at the main story position (III) six user features, where each event contains another, distinct user (IV) information on whether the user clicked on the article at the story position, or not.

More formally, for each event $t$ an article represents one of $k$ arms (that is, one of the 271 articles observed within the course of the 10 days covered by the data set) with $\mathbb{R}^6$ features $X_{t,a}$ per arm, and another $\mathbb{R}^6$ features $X_{t,u}$ per unique visitor. Together, the the flattened outer product of the user and article feature vector creates an $\mathbb{R}^36$ feature vector $X_t$ for each user and article pair with the outcome value or reward $r_t$) click (1) or no click (0).

As the Yahoo data was too large to fit into memory, we imported most\footnote{The first two CSV files of the Yahoo! data set contained irregularities, so we left those out of the import. That means that our simulations had 37,450,196 events available to them, instead of all 45,811,883. Still more than enough to replicate the original paper.} of the data set's CSV files into a MonetDB \cite{Idreos2012} instance---a very fast, open source column-oriented database management system with great R support\footnote{MonetDB can be downloaded at https://www.monetdb.org/}. The import script, example import scripts for several other databases (MySQL, SQLite, Postgresql), this replication's Bandit and Policy subclasses, and more can be found in the package's \code{demo/replication_li_2010 directory}.

With the Yahoo! data imported into the MonetDB server, the next steps were the creation of a Bandit subclass that would be able to query it, and the creation of Policy subclasses according to their description in the \cite{Li2010} paper. Since most of these Policies are already available in \pkg{contextual}, it would stand to reason that we would only have had to implement these. But as only a subset of all 271 articles or arms were shown for each seperate event, we had to make some minor changes to each of these Policy classes to make them run smoothly on the constantly shifting pool of available arms. We solved this by simply adding an "arms" vector containing the indexes of all currently active arms to the context list created by the Bandit. That is, in our YahooBandit we first create a \code{self$arm_lookup} table containing all arms, and then return the following in YahooBandit's \code{get_context()}:

<<eval=FALSE, size='small'>>=
    get_context = function(index) {
      ...
      # Retrieve the index of all arms this row/event.
      arm_indices_this_event   <- seq(10, 184, by = 7)
      article_ids              <- row[arm_indices_this_event]
      article_ids              <- article_ids[!is.na(article_ids)]
      article_ids              <- match(article_ids,self$arm_lookup)
      ...
      contextlist <- list(
        k = self$k,
        d = self$d,
        unique = self$unique, # <-- Indexes of all disjoint arms (user features)
        shared = self$shared, # <-- Indexes of all shared arms (article features)
        arms = article_ids,   # <-- Indexes of arms this event.
        X = X
      )
    }
@

And adapted each Policy accordingly, for example, in YahooEpsilonGreedyPolicy's \code{get_action()}:

<<eval=FALSE, size='small'>>=
    get_action = function(t, context) {
      if (runif(1) > self$epsilon) {
        # get the max of context$arms *currently in play*
        max_index            <- context$arms[max_in(theta$mean[context$arms])]
        self$action$choice   <- max_index
      } else {
        # sample from the arms *currently in play*
        self$action$choice   <- sample(context$arms, 1)
      }
      self$action
    }
@



